<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="NCGA Reusable Template System"
  description="Designed a multi-channel layout system and production templates for the North Carolina General Assembly, standardizing complex legislative publications and connecting print materials to digital workflows."
  seoTitle="NCGA Reusable Template System · Design Systems & Information Architecture"
  seoDescription="A multi-channel design system and layout standards serving 170+ legislative members at the North Carolina General Assembly, standardizing complex publications and connecting print collateral to digital channels."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Public-sector communications are dense, fast-moving, and legally sensitive.
    At the North Carolina General Assembly, our team supported 170+ legislative
    members producing a continuous stream of print and digital materials under
    tight deadlines. Without established visual standards, similar documents
    were rebuilt from scratch each cycle, causing production bottlenecks and
    inconsistent public presentation.
  </p>
  <p>
    I designed and launched a modular template system and layout standards that
    unified our print and digital channels. By defining structured typographic
    scales and reusable layout blocks, we accelerated production workflows,
    standardized complex publications, and connected physical outreach materials
    directly to digital state services.
  </p>

  <h2>The Information Scaling Challenge</h2>
  <p>
    Legislators communicate across diverse touchpoints—from highly structured,
    multi-page policy handbooks to quick constituent postcards. The challenge
    was twofold:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Varying content length.</strong> A postcard or town hall flyer might
      have three sentences or twenty, yet both had to look balanced, intentional,
      and authoritative.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Information density.</strong> Multi-page publications were packed with
      dense historical, statistical, and legislative text that constituents struggled
      to scan.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Fragmented production.</strong> Designers were manually recalculating
      margins, type hierarchies, and grid positions for every individual project,
      leading to high-friction handoffs and design drift.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Designing the Typographic and Layout Grid System</h2>
  <p>
    I created a layout system built around modular grids and rigid, highly
    scannable typographic scales. I defined explicit visual hierarchies to
    handle dense, complex public documents:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>High-density publications.</strong> I designed the layout system and
      typesetting for the <em>Sir Walter Cabinet handbook</em>, published twice,
      a prominent multi-page directory. Structured grids, side-navigation
      headers, and clear table styles transformed dense historical and
      leadership directories into a clean, editorial layout that is easy to
      navigate.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Modular legislative collateral.</strong> I designed a collection of
      reusable templates for town hall flyers and constituent postcards. These templates
      feature flexible, content-agnostic grid blocks that adapt to varying text lengths
      and portrait or landscape orientations without breaking the design.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Connecting Print to Digital Channels</h2>
  <p>
    Design systems do not stop at the edge of a page. I brought this systemic
    approach to HR’s recruitment and outreach efforts, designing a unified suite
    of career fair collateral—large-format tablecloths, posters, flyers, and
    handouts.
  </p>
  <p>
    To make these physical materials actionable, I designed a cross-channel QR
    code system. Rather than printing long URLs on posters, I integrated
    prominent, high-contrast QR targets with explicit calls to action. Physical
    attendees scanning a flyer or poster were directed straight to localized
    digital career portals and online application forms. This bridged physical
    interactions directly into digital recruitment workflows, improving data
    tracking and sign-up rates across 7+ events.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcomes</h2>
  <p>
    The template system transformed how our design team operates. By
    standardizing recurring layouts and typography, we cut production turnaround
    times for legislative materials in half, letting the team focus on complex,
    high-priority publications. The unified visual standards ensured a
    consistent, authoritative brand voice across all legislative channels, while
    improving readability and document accessibility for North Carolina
    citizens.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
